Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 475 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Dice @tomato{1}(diced). Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2%unit}(thinly sliced). Quarter @lime{1}(quartered). Core, deseed, and dice @green bell pepper{1}(diced into ½-inch pieces).

**Rinse @shrimp{10%ounce} under cold water; pat dry with paper towels.**

In a #small bowl{}, combine tomato, scallions, a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon}, and juice from one lime wedge (two wedges for 4 servings). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{3%tablespoon} with lime juice to taste. Add water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency. Season with salt and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper, salt, and pepper; cook until just softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add another drizzle of oil to pan. Add @ground pork{1%pound}, half the @Tex-Mex paste{1%tablespoon}, half the @Southwest Spice Blend{1%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest of each later), salt, and pepper. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until pork is browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Turn off heat.

> If there's excess grease in your pan, carefully pour it out.

Once veggies are just softened, cook through the rest of this step as instructed, swapping in shrimp or beef for pork. Cook, stirring frequently, until cooked through, ~{3-5%minutes} for shrimp or ~{4-6%minutes} for beef.

Place a small amount of filling on one half of each @flour tortillas{6}. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create enchiladas. Place, seam sides down, in an #8-by-8-inch baking dish{} (9-by-13-inch baking dish for 4 servings) or an #ovenproof pan{}.

In a #liquid measuring cup{}, combine ½ cup water (¾ cup for 4 servings), @tomato paste{1.5%ounce}, remaining Tex-Mex paste, and remaining Southwest Spice Blend.

Pour sauce over enchiladas to thoroughly coat. Sprinkle with @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}.

Bake on top rack until sauce is bubbly and cheese has melted, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Top enchiladas with lime crema and pico de gallo. Divide between plates and serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Shrimp are fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.